pr_title: Avoid server-side errors caused by nil
pr_body:
This may be a rare case, but I found some method calls with `nil`-able values.

The existence of errors is confirmed by the cooperation of @mame.

Footnote: This bug is found by static analysis with RBS, RBS Rails, and Steep.

As far as I've tried, README seemed to be a bit wrong.

* `list` subcommand should be placed after options like `--class`
* `interface` option also needs `--` prefix as same as `--class` or `--module`

In other words, `rbs list --interface` worked for me.

As of now, `rbs prototype runtime --require-relative` is identical with `... --require` because it uses `require()`, not `require_relative()`.

This PR changes `--require-relative` to use `require_relative()`.

With this change, the below command works as expected with local rails application.

```
bundle exec rbs prototype runtime --require-relative config/environment ModelName
```

(Note: I needed to add `Rails.application.eager_load!` to environment.rb for proper recognition of classes)

Although `rbs` has been renamed from `ruby-signature`, the old name still seems to be around in many places. This may lead to misunderstanding.

This PR tries to clean up those. I confirmed all tests with `rake` are passed, but I recommend checking manually with your eyes :eyes: before merging.

Note that there is still one line when you run `git grep ruby.signature`. This has remained on purpose because the line is a warning message of deprecation.

> lib/ruby/signature.rb:STDERR.puts "ðŸš¨ðŸš¨ ruby-signature is renamed to rbs. require 'rbs' instead of 'ruby/signature'. ðŸš¨ðŸš¨"

pr_title: Workaround: just skip anonymous superclasses and included modules
pr_body:
Fixes #301 and https://github.com/ruby/rbs/issues/301#issuecomment-641747375 based on the direction of https://github.com/ruby/rbs/issues/301#issuecomment-641726359.

For this `./c.rb`,

```ruby
class C < Class.new
  include Module.new
  def x; end
end
```

the command `bundle exec rbs prototype runtime --require ./c C` generates warning messages and  signatures:

```
W, [2020-06-10T15:39:12.732355 #28227]  WARN -- rbs: Skipping anonymous superclass #<Class:0x000055b123e491a0>
W, [2020-06-10T15:39:12.732475 #28227]  WARN -- rbs: Skipping anonymous module #<Module:0x000055b123e49010>
class C
  public

  def x: () -> untyped
end
```

pr_body:
This adds some type mappings that needed for real Rails apps.

* `:float` => `"Float"`
* `:binary` => `"String"`

Though it is a PostgreSQL-dependent feature, `inet` was needed to type Mastodon.
https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon
https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon/blob/ce9ae9aa50/db/schema.rb#L705

pr_title: Add a signature of `last` method for AR
pr_body: Add a signature of the `last` method as the same as `first`.

Just add a signature.

(IMHO, Typing `ActiveSupport::StringInquirer` like `Rails.env.test?` is a really hard thing. But it's another story :)

pr_title: Generate additional signatures for auto-generated AR methods
pr_body:
AR automatically creates some additional methods which correspond to DB columns.

* `ActiveRecord::Base` includes [`ActiveModel::Dirty`](https://api.rubyonrails.org/classes/ActiveModel/Dirty.html) 
  * We can use some auto-generated methods like `foo_changed?` or `foo_will_change!` for column `foo`
* `bar?` is also generated for `:boolean` column `bar`

It would be an advantage to developers if RBS Rails generated signatures for those auto-generated methods.

I tried `steep check` with [newly-generated signatures](https://github.com/tadd/mastodon/commit/e9e92889a15e3bce05775ff3bab914240139632c). It passed without syntactic errors.

pr_title: Earlier shutdown with interruption while `steep watch`
pr_body:
When I run `steep watch` by mistake, it took a long time to stop the steep process. This PR tries to make it shorter.

## Current Status of `master`

For example, if I run `steep watch` in a large project directory like [Mastodon](https://github.com/tootsuite/mastodon), it takes about **40 seconds** currently to stop the watching process with `Ctrl+C`:

```sh
$ time bundle exec steep --log-level=fatal watch app/models/
[deprecation warnings omitted]
ðŸ‘€ Watching directories, Ctrl-C to stop.
^CShutting down workers... # I typed Ctrl+C immediately after ðŸ‘€ printed

real	0m40.593s
user	0m48.878s
sys	0m1.637s
```

## After PR Applied

It takes only **4 seconds** if this PR applied.

```sh
$ time bundle exec steep --log-level=error watch app/models/
[deprecation warnings omitted]
ðŸ‘€ Watching directories, Ctrl-C to stop.
^CShutting down workers...

real	0m4.045s
user	0m6.723s
sys	0m1.438s
```
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 462001700, 'comment_body': 'Currently, if the running process was interrupted, `shutdown` and `exit` messages are sent.

I added to sleep for a while then interrupt the master worker because sending messages does not mean worker processes stop immediately.   `master.interrupt` yields all child worker processes are stopped soon.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 2, 31, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tadd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 462002953, 'comment_body': 'Worker processes can be stopped earlier by sending signals.

In my environment, SIGINT was not effective sometimes. Because of that, I added some lines to send a signal again with SIGTERM.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 29, 2, 36, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tadd', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 465102505, 'comment_body': 'After `Interrupt`, wait for `main_thread` again with timeout value.
If the timeout was occured, `master.intterupt` was called because  `Thread#join` returns `nil`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 4, 14, 40, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'tadd', 'type': 'User'}]
